HTML Web Pag Research and Code analysis
Example 1- HTML Form Page
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
<h2>HTML Forms</h2>
<form action="/action_page.php">
<label for="fname">First name:</label><br>
<input type="text" id="fname" name="fname" value="John"><br>
<label for="lname">Last name:</label><br>
<input type="text" id="lname" name="lname" value="Doe"><br><br>
<input type="submit" value="Submit">
</form>
<p>If you click the "Submit" button, the form-data will be sent to a page called
"/action_page.php".</p>
</body>
</html>


Code Analysis
A. Structure Analysis
The structure begins with the declaration !DOCTYPE html. This declaration is used to inform the
browser that this is an HTML5 document.
The structure contains the HTML elements, namely, the html and body elements. However, the
head element is missing in this structure. In a complete HTML document, the head section is
used to include metadata such as the page title, character encoding, and possibly links to
stylesheets or scripts.
The structure is well indented, making it easy to understand the structure of the HTML elements
in this document.
The correct structure should include:
* head element
* title tag
* meta tags for accessibility and search engine optimization


B. Elements and Tags

In this example, the heading tag h2 is used to display the page title, "HTML Forms."
The page does not include any lists, such as the unordered list tag or the ordered list tag.
Instead, this page is focused on form elements.
The main elements in this page are:

* form, which is used to collect user input
* label>, which is used to describe the input fields
* input fields, where users can insert text
* input type="submit" for form submission
No images are present in this example. Additionally, there are no hyperlinks (a tags).
The form inputs are correctly associated with their respective labels using the for attribute.


C. Semantic HTML5 Usage

There is no usage of semantic HTML5 tags in the code. These tags include:
● header
● nav
● section
● article
● main
● footer
Improvement can be made by adding the content inside the following tags:
A. main for the main content
B. header for the title
C. footer for additional content


Example 2- Radio Button
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
<h2>Radio Buttons</h2>
<p>Choose your favorite Web language:</p>
<form>
<input type="radio" id="html" name="fav_language" value="HTML">
<label for="html">HTML</label><br>
<input type="radio" id="css" name="fav_language" value="CSS">
<label for="css">CSS</label><br>
<input type="radio" id="javascript" name="fav_language" value="JavaScript">
<label for="javascript">JavaScript</label>
</form>
</body>
</html>


Code Analysis
A. Structure Analysis
The structure of this HTML document starts with the declaration !DOCTYPE html. This means
the document is written in HTML5.
The document has the html and body elements. However, the document is missing the head
element. A basic HTML document needs the head element to hold metadata such as the title
and character encoding.
The structure is well indented and very presentable. The structure is well arranged since every
element in the form is on a separate line.
However, the structure needs improvement in the following ways:
head
title
metadata elements

B. Elements and Tags
The document makes use of the h2 tag for the heading "Radio Buttons."
The document makes use of the p tag for the user's instruction.
The main elements in this document are the elements found in the form:
form
input type="radio"
label
Radio buttons allow the user to choose only one option from a group. This is done by giving all
the radio buttons the same name attribute:
<form>
<label><input type="radio" name="fav_language" value="Java">Java</label>
<label><input type="radio" name="fav_language" value="C++">C++</label>
<label><input type="radio" name="fav_language" value="PHP">PHP</label>
</form>
There are no lists, images, or links in this document.
The labels are correctly associated with the radio buttons through the for attribute.


C. Semantic HTML5 Usage
This webpage doesn’t utilize semantic HTML5 tags like:
● header
● nav
● section
● article
● main
● footer
To make the code structure and readability better, semantic elements can be included.


Example 3- Checkbox Form Page
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
<h2>Checkboxes</h2>
<p>The <strong>input type="checkbox"</strong> defines a checkbox:</p>
<form action="/action_page.php">
<input type="checkbox" id="vehicle1" name="vehicle1" value="Bike">
<label for="vehicle1"> I have a bike</label><br>
<input type="checkbox" id="vehicle2" name="vehicle2" value="Car">
<label for="vehicle2"> I have a car</label><br>
<input type="checkbox" id="vehicle3" name="vehicle3" value="Boat">
<label for="vehicle3"> I have a boat</label><br><br>
<input type="submit" value="Submit">
</form>
</body>
</html>


Code Analysis
A. Structure Analysis
The document starts with the HTML5 doctype declaration, which is !DOCTYPE html. This is
essential because it instructs the browser to render the HTML5 code.
The document has the HTML and body tags, but it does not have the head section. The HTML
document is not complete because it is supposed to have the head section that contains
metadata and the title.
The code has proper indentation, which makes it easy to read and maintain.

B. Elements and Tags
The document has the heading tag h2 that is used to display the title "Checkboxes".
The paragraph element p is used to explain what the checkbox is. Inside the paragraph
element, the strong tag is used to stress the phrase input type="checkbox".
The main tags used in the document include:

form
input type="checkbox"
label
input type="submit”
The checkboxes allow the user to choose more than one option at the same time.
The labels are correctly referencing the corresponding input elements using the for attribute.


C. Semantic HTML5 Usage
This page does not use any semantic HTML5 elements such as:
● header
● nav
● section
● article
● main
● footer
To improve this structure, the form could be placed inside the main element, and the heading
could be placed inside the header element.
